ng to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Grey","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English, Scottish, and Irish: variant of   Gray  .","German: dialect variant of   Grau  .","In some cases also an American shortened and altered form of Ukrainian <b>Grushko</b>: nickname or topographic name derived from a Russian-influenced transliteration of <i>grushka</i> ‘pear, pear tree’."],"variants":[{"name":"Gray","meanings":["English, Scottish, and Irish (especially Eastern Ulster; of Norman origin): habitational name from Graye in Calvados, France, named from the Gallo-Roman personal name <i>Graec(i)us</i>, meaning ‘Greek’ + the locative suffix <i>-acum</i>. This is probably the chief source of the surname in Britain.","English: nickname for someone with gray hair or a gray beard, from Middle English <i>grey</i> (Old English <i>grǣg</i>, <i>grēg</i>) ‘gray’. In Ireland it has been used as a translation of various Gaelic surnames derived from <i>riabhach</i> ‘brindled, gray’, including <b>Mac Giolla Riabhaigh</b>; see   McGreevy  . In North America, this surname has assimilated names with similar meaning from other languages.","French: habitational name from Gray in Haute-Saône or Le Gray in Seine-Maritime."]},{"name":"Greiwe","meanings":["German: possibly a nickname from Middle High German <i>greibe</i> ‘sharp, tangy, dour’. Compare   Grey  ."]}]},{"name":"Agnes","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized version of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Agnes de Grey was born about 1212, in Codnor, Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom. She had at least 1 son with William FitzThomas Sr.. She died in her hometown."},"et":{"ABT 1212–":"umbes 1212–Surnud","1214–1294":"1214–1294","1235–1295":"1235–1295","1212–Female":"1212–Surnud","abt 1235":"umbes 1235","1214":"1214","1235":"1235","1212":"1212","ABT 1212":"umbes 1212","1295":"1295","1294":"1294","Codnor,Derbyshire,England Place":"Codnor, Derbyshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Codnor,Derbyshire,England":"Codnor, Derbyshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Emley, York, England":"Emley, Yorkshire, England"},"fi":{"ABT 1212–":"noin 1212–Kuollut","1214–1294":"1214–1294","1235–1295":"1235–1295","1212–Female":"1212–Kuollut","abt 1235":"noin 1235","1214":"1214","1235":"1235","1212":"1212","ABT 1212":"noin 1212","1295":"1295","1294":"1294","Codnor,Derbyshire,England Place":"Codnor, Derbyshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Codnor,Derbyshire,England":"Codnor, Derbyshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Emley, York, England":"Emley, Yorkshire, England"},"fr":{"ABT 1212–":"environ 1212–Décédée","1214–1294":"1214–1294","1235–1295":"1235–1295","1212–Female":"1212–Décédée","abt 1235":"environ 1235","1214":"1214","1235":"1235","1212":"1212","ABT 1212":"environ 1212","1295":"1295","1294":"1294","Codnor,Derbyshire,England Place":"Codnor, Derbyshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Codnor,Derbyshire,England":"Codnor, Derbyshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Emley, York, England":"Emley, Everwyck, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Agnes de Grey est née environ 1212, à Codnor, Derbyshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. Elle a eu au moins 1 fils avec William FitzThomas Sr.. Elle est décéd